="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-35-calculating-horizontal-hoops-for-the-petticoat-and-ruffles-for-the-casing/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-35-calculating-horizontal-hoops-for-the-petticoat-and-ruffles-for-the-casing/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-08T18:35:17+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-08T18:35:17+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 35. Calculating Horizontal Hoops for the Petticoat and Ruffles for the Casing."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 35. Calculating Horizontal Hoops for the Petticoat and Ruffles for the Casing."><meta itemprop="description" content="Let's first calculate hoop positions for a petticoat without ruffles and then calculate ruffles for its fabric casing."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 35. Calculating Horizontal Hoops for the Petticoat and Ruffles for the Casing.</h1><p><strong>Let us first calculate hoop positions for a petticoat without ruffles and then calculate ruffles for its fabric casing. </strong></p><p><strong>If there are no ruffles on the petticoat itself, then you need to know the lengths of its steel hoops, as well as where they are supposed to be positioned. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us take a petticoat with six hoops for example. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2035.files/image015.jpg" alt="goldub-645"></strong></p><p><strong>Please note a very important condition: </strong></p><p>- If the first ruffle goes along the waistline (line 0) and the last sixths ruffle goes along line 5,</p><p>- then the tunnel for the first petticoat hoop should go along line 1 and the tunnel for the last sixths hoop – directly along the bottom edge of the petticoat (line 6).</p><p><strong>For this reason, you will have to choose between two options if you select 6 for the number of ruffles in the table:</strong></p><p><strong>- If you are making ruffles, </strong>then use the suggested lengths of ruffles 1-6,</p><p><strong>- If you are making hoop tunnels,</strong> then use the suggested lengths of ruffles 2-6, as well as the Total Hem Length for the bottom tunnel.</p><p><strong>Let us see what these automatic calculations will look like. </strong></p><p><strong>We are working with the already familiar Table for Calculating a Skirt Based on Hem Length (Horizontal Ruffles tab). </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2035.files/image017.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I fill in the key skirt parameters as usual. </strong></p><p><strong>Then, I set the key parameters of horizontal ruffles: </strong></p><p>- Number of Skirt Ruffles (without Train) – 6,</p><p>- Ruffles Overlap – 0. We are making hoop tunnels.</p><p>- Ruffle Gathering Ratio – 0. For the same reason as above.</p><p>- Width of Ruffle Fabric – 150cm.</p><p><strong>Let us see: </strong></p><p>- Calculated ruffle sewing edge lengths are, at the same time, steel hoop lengths or hoop tunnel lengths,</p><p>- And the distance from waistline shows where each tunnel should be positioned on the petticoat.</p><p><strong>As I already mentioned, remember </strong>to look for the parameters of the first petticoat hoop in the line for ruffle 2, the parameters of the second hoop – in the line for ruffle 3, and the parameters of the last hoop – in the Total Hem Length line.</p><p><strong>So, the table has calculated hoop lengths for a petticoat with six hoops: </strong></p><p><strong>Hoop 1</strong> has a length of 110cm and is positioned 16.7cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>Hoop 2</strong> has a length of 140cm and is positioned 33.3cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>Hoop 3</strong> has a length of 180cm and is positioned 50cm below waistline. This hoop will be placed in the very middle of the petticoat because the given skirt length is 100cm.</p><p><strong>Hoop 4</strong> has a length of 210cm and is positioned 66.7cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>Hoop 5</strong> has a length of 240cm and is positioned 83.3cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>Hoop 6</strong> has a length of 270cm (what we wanted initially) and is positioned along the bottom edge of the skirt, i.e. 100cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>You can see the results of these calculations in the drawing below. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2035.files/image018.jpg" alt="goldub-647"></strong></p><p><strong>I would also like to point out that you can remove as many top hoops as you want. </strong>In other words, after doing calculations for a petticoat with six hoops, you can simply leave out the top tunnels if you don’t need them and turn it into a petticoat with three or four hoops instead.</p><p><strong>So we have calculated our petticoat hoops and now let us do necessary calculations for a matching fabric casing with, for example, five ruffles on it. </strong></p><p><strong>But first let me make a small foreword. </strong></p><p><strong>Firstly, </strong>the casing itself must be a little wider and looser than the petticoat. While we used a sector angle of 109 degrees for the petticoat, we will make it 120 degrees for the fabric casing. By increasing the sector angle, we will automatically increase the circumference of the fabric casing: it will be 290cm at the level of 100cm below waistline as compared to 270cm on the petticoat.</p><p><strong>Secondly,</strong> the fabric casing will be cut 10cm longer than the petticoat. Its front length will be 110cm.</p><p><strong>And thirdly, </strong>our fabric casing will feature a small train with ruffles. For this reason, its back length will be 140cm.</p><p><strong>We are using the same Table for Calculating a Skirt Based on Hem Length (Horizontal Ruffles tab). </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2035.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I put the key initial parameters in the table (red arrows): </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 80cm,</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 110cm,</p><p>- Back Seam Length (Train Included) – 140cm,</p><p>- Desired Sector Angle – 120 degrees,</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.</p><p><strong>And I fill in the key parameters of horizontal ruffles: </strong></p><p>- Number of Ruffles – 5,</p><p>- Ruffles Overlap – 3cm,</p><p>- Ruffle Gathering Ratio – 3. Let us assume we will cut our ruffles from hard mesh fabric.</p><p>- Width of Ruffle Fabric – 150cm.</p><p><strong>We get the following Calculated Ruffle Parameters (blue arrows): </strong></p><p>- Intervals – 21.4cm,</p><p>- Ruffle Strip Width (Seam Allowances Included) – 26.8cm. It is the width of the initial strip of fabric.</p><p>- Finished Ruffle Width – 24.4cm.</p><p><strong>Let us scroll down to see how much fabric we need for these ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2035.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p>- Fabric Consumption Starting from Second Ruffle – 6.2m,</p><p>- Fabric Consumption Starting from Third Ruffle –5.4m,</p><p>- Fabric Consumption Starting from Fourth Ruffle – 4.6m,</p><p>- Fabric Consumption Starting from Fifth Ruffle –3.5m.</p><p><strong>This shows us </strong>that if we divide the fabric casing in five parts following the ruffle sewing lines (with the first ruffle going along the waistline and the last (fifth) ruffle going along the bottom edge), then:</p><p>- we will need 3.5m of mesh fabric with a width of 150cm if we want to make only one bottom ruffle with a width of 24.4cm,</p><p>- we will need 4.6m of mesh fabric if we decide to add another ruffle at the bottom, etc.,</p><p>- and we will need as much as 6.2m of mesh fabric to cover the full fabric casing with ruffles.</p><p><strong>This way you can decide it for yourself how many ruffles you want to keep and see how much fabric you need in that case. </strong></p><p><strong>Next, let us scroll up a bit and look at the following parameters: </strong></p><p>- Total Fabric Consumption for All Ruffles is 6.7m. Remember that our fabric casing features a small 30cm-long train with some ruffles on it, too.</p><p>- Fabric Consumption for Skirt Ruffles (train excluded) – 4.6m,</p><p>- Fabric Consumption for Train Ruffles – 2.1m.</p><p><strong>As I said before, we get another important parameter: </strong></p><p>- Total Hem Length (train included) – 3.4m.</p><p><strong>This parameter is particularly useful </strong>when you go to buy lace or some other decorative material for finishing the hem of your skirt. Such materials are usually quite expensive, and this way you will know how much exactly you need.</p><p><strong>Total Sewing Edge Length of All Ruffles is also very useful. It is 8.5m in our case (12.3m including the train). </strong>This parameter would be essential if we were making not a fabric casing but some kind of an overlay skirt with or without train and decided to replace ruffles with flounces.</p><p><strong>Open the Flounces tab of our table. </strong></p><p><strong>Fill in the necessary initial parameters: </strong></p><p>- Total Sewing Edge Length of All Ruffles (train excluded) – 8.5m,</p><p>- Width of Ruffle Fabric – 150cm.</p><p><strong>The table calculates the following things based on these parameters: </strong></p><p>- Finished Ruffle Width and its Sewing Edge Length,</p><p>- Ruffle Strip Length and Width,</p><p>- Number of Ruffles (17) and Total Fabric Consumption for All Ruffles (2.3m).</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2035.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let us return to the Horizontal Ruffles tab and continue discussing the results of our calculations: </strong></p><p>- Number of Train Ruffles – 2,</p><p>- Total Sewing Edge Length of Train Ruffles – 3.8m,</p><p>- Hem Length (Train Excluded) – 3.2m.</p><p><strong>And now let us take a closer look at the Hem Length (Train Excluded), which is 3.2m in our case. </strong></p><p><strong>There is a schematic drawing of our petticoat (green lines) and its fabric casing (red lines) on the writing board below.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2035.files/image025.jpg" alt="goldub-651"></p><p>We chose a sector angle of 109 degrees <strong>when we were constructing the petticoat, </strong>and the resulting length of the bottom hoop was 270cm at the level of 100cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>When we were constructing a fabric casing for this petticoat, </strong>we decided to make it wider and increased the sector angle up to 120 degrees. We also made the casing 10cm longer than the petticoat, i.e. 110cm.</p><p><strong>In this case though, </strong>the fabric casing will have a circumference of 290cm at the level of the bottom petticoat hoop (100cm below waistline) and its hem will be 320cm long (train excluded) and positioned at the level of 110cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>And please note </strong>that the sector angle also influences the waist opening radius so that the waist edge remains a constant value both for the petticoat, as well as for the fabric casing. It is equal to the initially given 80cm.</p><p><strong>Let us go back to the table. </strong></p><p><strong>We can see </strong>the length of <strong>each of the five ruffles </strong>(with regard to gathering ratio), its sewing edge length (down to which the strip of fabric needs to be gathered before you sew it to the fabric casing), and the distance between its sewing line and the waistline.</p><p><strong>Here are these parameters for ruffle 1 </strong>going right along the waistline:</p><p>- Ruffle Length with Regard to Gathering Ratio – 2.4m,</p><p>- Sewing Edge Length which corresponds with Waist Circumference – 0.8m (80cm).</p><p><strong>Ruffle 2:</strong></p><p>- Ruffle Length with Regard to Gathering Ratio – 3.7m,</p><p>- Sewing Edge Length – 1.2m,</p><p>- Distance to Waistline – 21.4cm.</p><p><strong>Ruffle 3:</strong></p><p>- Ruffle Length with Regard to Gathering Ratio – 5.1m,</p><p>- Sewing Edge Length – 1.7m,</p><p>- Distance to Waistline – 42.8cm.</p><p><strong>Ruffle 4:</strong></p><p>- Ruffle Length with Regard to Gathering Ratio – 6.4m,</p><p>- Sewing Edge Length – 2.1m,</p><p>- Distance to Waistline – 64.2cm.</p><p><strong>Ruffle 5:</strong></p><p>- Ruffle Length with Regard to Gathering Ratio – 7.8m,</p><p>- Sewing Edge Length – 2.6m,</p><p>- Distance to Waistline – 85.6cm.</p><p><strong>The table has also calculated necessary parameters of ruffles for the train of the fabric casing. </strong></p><p><strong>There are only two ruffles on the train. </strong></p><p><strong>Train Ruffle 1:</strong></p><p>- Ruffle Length with Regard to Gathering Ratio – 5.3m,</p><p>- Sewing Edge Length – 1.8m,</p><p>- Distance to Waistline – 110cm.</p><p><strong>Train Ruffle 2:</strong></p><p>- Ruffle Length with Regard to Gathering Ratio – 6.0m,</p><p>- Sewing Edge Length – 2.0m,</p><p>- Distance to Waistline – 131.4cm.</p><p><strong>It is clear from the suggested ruffles layout that: </strong></p><p><strong>- ruffle 1</strong> goes basically along the very bottom of the fabric casing,</p><p><strong>- and ruffle 2</strong> goes at 21.4cm from ruffle 1.</p><p>The overlap is 3cm.</p><p><strong>Of course, these train ruffles require some adjustments. </strong>When you start sewing the garment, you will have to think over how to put them on it and what shape to give them (maybe they will look better when narrower at the sides and wider in the middle). And you should also decide about the function of these ruffles on this train: are they just decorative elements or are they supposed to reinforce the train, lift it up from the ground, etc?</p><p>So it has taken us basically just a minute to get a full layout for cutting a petticoat and a fabric casing with train and ruffles.</p><p>We were doing it for the first time and my long comments were just to explain how to use these automatic calculation tables.</p><p><strong>Once you learn how to use my tables and get the point behind the calculations and how the programme works, you will be able to calculate all necessary parameters for your garment within a couple of minutes as long as you have precise initial data and fill them in correctly. </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlinaFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><h3>Skirt Patterns:</h3><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Patterns/flaredSkirt.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Flared Skirt - Scale 1:2</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Patterns/flaredSkirtBig.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacade